<h2>Overview</h2>

<img
  src={`${base}/images/origins/ethiopia.jpg`}
  alt="Ethiopian coffee farm"
  style="width:100%;border-radius:12px;margin:1rem 0 1.5rem;object-fit:cover;max-height:360px;"
/>

<p>
  Ethiopia is the only country recognized as coffee's true origin — the genetic homeland of <em>Coffea arabica</em>. Wild coffee trees still grow in the montane forests of southwestern Ethiopia, particularly in Kaffa and Illubabor regions, where they have grown without human cultivation for thousands of years. These forests represent the world's most significant reservoir of coffee genetic diversity.
</p>

<p>
  The most famous legend of coffee's discovery traces to a 9th-century Ethiopian goatherd named <strong>Kaldi</strong>, who noticed his goats became energetic after eating red berries from a certain tree. He brought the berries to a nearby monastery, where monks brewed a drink that kept them alert through long evening prayers. The story's historical accuracy matters less than its cultural truth: coffee's identity is inseparable from Ethiopia's.
</p>

<div class="info-box">
  <h4>Ethiopia at a Glance</h4>
  <p>
    <strong>Varieties:</strong> Heirloom landraces (thousands of distinct genotypes)<br />
    <strong>Processing:</strong> Washed (wet) and Natural (dry)<br />
    <strong>Harvest:</strong> October–February (varies by region and altitude)<br />
    <strong>Altitude:</strong> 1,500–2,200m (exceptional lots above 2,300m)<br />
    <strong>Production:</strong> ~450,000–500,000 metric tons/year — Africa's largest producer
  </p>
</div>

<h2>Geography and Climate</h2>

<p>
  Coffee cultivation concentrates in the southern and southwestern highlands. The Great Rift Valley cuts through the country north to south; the highland plateaus on either side provide ideal growing conditions. Specialty-grade coffee typically comes from <strong>1,500–2,200m altitude</strong>; some exceptional single-farm lots come from above 2,300m.
</p>

<p>
  Climate is tropical highland — annual average temperatures of 15–24°C, rainfall of 1,200–2,000mm. The main rainy season (Kiremt) runs June–September; a shorter season (Belg) covers March–May. Harvest is October–February, varying by region and elevation. The slow cherry maturation at high altitude, driven by cool nights and warm days, is central to Ethiopia's flavor complexity.
</p>

<p>
  Four production systems coexist: <strong>Forest Coffee</strong> (wild trees harvested from natural forest), <strong>Semi-Forest Coffee</strong> (minimal human management of wild trees), <strong>Garden Coffee</strong> (smallholder plots mixed with other crops around homesteads), and <strong>Plantation Coffee</strong> (organized, managed estates). The vast majority of Ethiopian specialty coffee comes from garden and semi-forest systems run by smallholder farmers.
</p>

