<p>
  <strong>Yirgacheffe</strong>, located in the Gedeo Zone, is Ethiopia's most prestigious region. Rich volcanic soils, consistently high altitude, and abundant rainfall produce remarkably aromatic coffee. Its name translates roughly to "marshy land near water," reflecting its water-rich landscape — ideal for the washing stations that produce its signature washed-process cups.
</p>

<p>
  <strong>Guji</strong> was formerly classified under Sidama but has earned recognition as a distinct origin in recent years, driven by exceptional natural-processed lots at high altitudes that deliver some of the world's most intense fruit-forward profiles.
</p>

<h2>Ethiopia's Varieties — The World's Most Diverse</h2>

<p>
  Ethiopian coffee doesn't rely on a handful of named varieties — it draws from <strong>thousands of genetically distinct heirloom landraces</strong> collectively called "Ethiopian heirloom" or "JARC varieties" (from the Jimma Agricultural Research Center, which has catalogued and selected many). This genetic richness means Ethiopian coffee is inherently more complex than single-variety lots from other origins.
</p>

<p>
  Many top specialty roasters specifically seek Ethiopian lots without defined variety names — "heirloom" is not a marketing euphemism but a reflection of genuine biodiversity. The diversity of Ethiopia's wild coffee gene pool is one of the specialty industry's most valuable (and fragile) resources.
</p>

<h2>Processing: Two Traditions</h2>

<p>
  Ethiopia produces world-class examples of both major processing methods:
</p>

<p>
  <strong>Washed (wet process)</strong> — Dominant in Yirgacheffe, Sidama, and Limu. Ripe cherries are delivered daily to central washing stations (wet mills) serving thousands of smallholders. After pulping and fermentation (typically 36–72 hours, depending on altitude and temperature), the clean seeds dry on raised African beds. The result is a coffee where the bean's intrinsic character — especially floral aromatics — shines without interference.
</p>

<p>
  <strong>Natural (dry process)</strong> — Traditional in Harrar and increasingly popular for specialty lots in Guji, Sidama, and Yirgacheffe. Whole cherries dry on raised beds for 2–6 weeks. Ethiopian naturals, particularly from Guji and Harrar, produce some of the world's most intense blueberry and wine-like flavors in any coffee — a direct product of the extended fruit fermentation around the seed.
</p>

<h2>The Coffee Ceremony</h2>

<p>
  Ethiopia's coffee culture extends far beyond agriculture. The <strong>Ethiopian coffee ceremony</strong> — a ritual that can last 1–2 hours — is central to social life. Green beans are roasted in a pan over an open flame in front of guests (the aroma itself is part of the ritual), ground with a mortar and pestle, and brewed in a clay pot called a <em>jebena</em>. The coffee is served in small cups, traditionally three rounds (Abol, Tona, Baraka), each progressively weaker. Frankincense is burned alongside the coffee.
</p>

<p>
  This ceremony isn't a tourist attraction — it's daily life for millions of Ethiopians. Roughly half of all coffee Ethiopia produces is consumed domestically, a rate unparalleled among coffee-producing nations. Ethiopia doesn't just produce coffee for the world; it lives with it.
</p>

